Heat the oil in a heavy-based pan over a medium heat and add the onion. Cook for 10 minutes, or until translucent. Stir in the garlic and rice and toast for a few minutes. Pour in the wine and cook, stirring, until evaporated.Meanwhile, heat the chicken stock. Stir a ladleful of hot stock into the rice until it has been absorbed. Keep adding the stock, a ladleful at a time, adding the saffron halfway through cooking, until the rice is nearly cooked.Remove the rice from the heat, stir in the butter and leave covered for 4 minutes. Stir in the Parmesan and then spread the mixture onto a cool baking sheet until ready to use.Meanwhile, to make the sauce, heat the oil in a pan over a medium heat and fry the garlic, chilli and basil stalks lightly for 5 minutes. Stir in the tomatoes and simmer for 20 minutes.Remove the tomatoes from the heat and blend using a hand blender. Stir in the basil leaves and leave to one side in a warm place until ready to serve.Fry the rashers of pancetta with the rosemary until crisp in a pan. Tip into a food-processor with the ciabatta and blend into breadcrumbs. Tip the mixture into a bowl.In a bowl, combine all the remaining ingredients, other than the egg, mix well and form into 16 balls.Pack the cooled rice around the filling ball and brush each with beaten egg and then roll through the breadcrumb mixture until covered.Heat a deep fryer to 180C, or until a cube of bread browns in 20 seconds (CAUTION: hot oil can be dangerous. Do not leave unattended.). Deep fry the arancini in batches for 2â€“3 minutes until golden. Remove from the oil with a slotted spoon and drain on kitchen paper.Serve with the arabiatta sauce.